Introduction


Racist graffiti was found on UW-Madisons campus in March of 2020 and again in September. According to the annual FBI hate crime report, hate crimes in Wisconsin rose 44% between 2019 to 2020 1. However, hate crimes are not a new phenomenon, and racist graffiti is certainly not new to UW-Madison. It is important to continue investigating the prevalence and types of hate crimes committed in our community.

In this report, we examine the most common types of hate crimes reported in 2013 using hate crime statistics from the FBI. Our data present statistics from agencies who reported one or more hate crime incidents during at least 1 quarter in 2013 2. According to our analysis, we find evidence that Hate Crimes related to race were 50% of Hate Crimes committed in Wisconsin according to the FBI in 2013.

Background


Since 1996, the FBI has been required to collect hate crime data through the Uniform Crime Reporting (UCR) Program annually. This data comes from city, county, college and university, state, tribal, and federal agencies. Hate crime statistics are made publicly available every year. According to the FBI, a hate crime is a crime which is motivated, in whole or in part, by the offenders bias(es) against a: race, religion, disability, sexual orientation, ethnicity, gender, gender identity 3. This is even if the offender incorrectly perceives the victim as a member of a certain group. This data is collected by either voluntary reporting from agencies or through investigation by law enforcement officers. These incidents are then reported to the FBI UCR program from where this data was collected 4.

Analyzing the types and likelihood of hate crimes help determine which states are at higher risk for certain dangers. This helps marginalized populations living in these states remain aware and vigilant. Additionally, it helps inform policy makers of local and state governments about what changes need to be made to help support marginalized populations 5. It can help inform governments as to how efficiently allocate budgets as well. Keeping track of changes in the trends of the amount and type of hate crimes can then help prove or disprove whether certain policy changes were effective or not. This is relevant because hate crime offenders are not always prosecuted so its integral to community safety to monitor changes in these statistics.

Some argue that hate crimes in more recent years have increased due to a backlash against BLM protests and Anti-Asian hate due to the pandemic, so it will be interesting to look at 2013 specifically and see what the trends were before these larger political/social events occurred. This can also allow us to see if there truly has been a change in the types/prevalence of hate crimes since then.

Specifically in Wisconsin, hate crime reporting is not required by law enforcement ( of states in U.S) and hate crime training for law enforcement officers is not provided ( of states in U.S) 6 Wisconsin law also offers alternative sentencing for hate crime offenders like mediation. Hate crime laws vary state by state so we thought that looking specifically at Wisconsins data trends would be interesting and relevant as students of UW-Madison.

Is the proportion of race crimes in Wisconsin 0.5? (Hypothesis Testing)

  • Null Hypothesis: \(p_0 = 0.5\)

  • Alternative Hypothesis: \(p_0 \neq 0.5\)

  • Test Statistic: \(X\), number of race hate crime

  • By null hypothesis, \(X\sim Bin(41,0.5)\)

  • Do a two tail hypothesis test and calculate the \(p\) value, which is \(P(X\leq18) + P(X\geq23)\)

  • The resulting p value is .5327. As the P-value is higher than 0.05, we cannot prove with a high degree of statistical certainty that the proportion of race hate crimes in Wisconsin is not .5.

  • The evidence is consistent with Hate Crimes related to race being 50% of Hate Crimes committed in Wisconsin according to the FBI in 2013 (p = 0.53, two tail Binomial test)

Discussion


This project investigated the prevalence of reported race hate crimes in Wisconsin in 2013. Through our graphics, we also explored the top 10 states with the most reported hate crimes, the difference in the number of hate crimes reported across quarters, as well as the most reported types of hate crimes in Wisconsin.

We can see from the two tail Binomial test that the proportion of race hate crimes in Wisconsin in 2013 is 50%. There was insufficient evidence to conclude that the proportion is more or less than .5. We also would expect the proportion of race hate crimes in Wisconsin in 2013 to be between .29 and .59 according to the confidence interval. This is consistent with what we observed. |
From this analysis we learned that race hate crimes are the most reported, and may be the most prevalent type of hate crime in Wisconsin in 2013. Our finding is important as police and other agencies that investigate these types of crimes have limited resources, thus, by finding the most prevalent type of crime we can better direct resources and funding to address the most pressing problems.

There are many avenues for future research. One would be to gather more data from the years between 2013 and now to examine trends over time. This would also increase our sample size and increase accuracy of our analysis. Another interesting direction to explore would be looking at more urban cities versus more rural cities and comparing the prevalence of different types of hate crimes. We would also be interested to see if there is a temporal relationship between protests and hate crimes. For example, were more hate crimes committed/reported after a BLM protest? Compared to before there was a protest or compared to the past average in that place? Does this change with the amount of protests occurring in a year?

One limitation of our project is our small sample size due to only looking at one year and one state specifically. Additionally, hate crimes reported may not fully capture the actual prevalence of hate crimes, as different states have different rules for what classifies as a hate crime, and victims may not report these crimes for various reasons.
